## Factoring

As a first step, we can take out a common factor:

$\begin{align}
p(x)&=3x^3-3x^2-18x
\\\\
&=3x(x^2-x-6)
\end{align}$

Now we can further factor $(x^2-x-6)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}3x\blueD{(x^2-x-6)}
\\\\
&=3x\blueD{(x-3)(x+2)}
\end{align}$

## Factoring

As a first step, we can take out a common factor:

$\begin{align}
p(x)&=2x^3+4x^2-6x
\\\\
&=2x(x^2+2x-3)
\end{align}$

Now we can further factor $(x^2+2x-3)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}2x\blueD{(x^2+2x-3)}
\\\\
&=2x\blueD{(x+3)(x-1)}
\end{align}$

## Factoring

As a first step, we can take out a common factor:

$\begin{align}
p(x)&=5x^3-5x^2-10x
\\\\
&=5x(x^2-x-2)
\end{align}$

Now we can further factor $(x^2-x-2)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}5x\blueD{(x^2-x-2)}
\\\\
&=5x\blueD{(x-2)(x+1)}
\end{align}$

## Factoring

$p$ is already partially factored. We can further factor $(x^2-1)$ using the difference of squares pattern:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\blueD{(x^2-1)}(x^2-5x+6)
\\\\
&=\blueD{(x+1)(x-1)}(x^2-5x+6)
\end{align}$

Now we can further factor $(x^2-5x+6)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}(x+1)(x-1)\purpleC{(x^2-5x+6)}
\\\\
&=(x+1)(x-1)\purpleC{(x-3)(x-2)}
\end{align}$

## Factoring

$p$ is already partially factored. We can further factor $(x^2-4)$ using the difference of squares pattern:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}(x^2+4x+3)\blueD{(x^2-4)}
\\\\
&=(x^2+4x+3)\blueD{(x+2)(x-2)}
\end{align}$

Now we can further factor $(x^2+4x+3)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\purpleC{(x^2+4x+3)}(x+2)(x-2)
\\\\
&=\purpleC{(x+3)(x+1)}(x+2)(x-2)
\end{align}$

## Factoring

$p$ is already partially factored. We can further factor $(x^2-9)$ using the difference of squares pattern:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\blueD{(x^2-9)}(x^2+x-2)
\\\\
&=\blueD{(x+3)(x-3)}(x^2+x-2)
\end{align}$

Now we can further factor $(x^2+x-2)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}(x+3)(x-3)\purpleC{(x^2+x-2)}
\\\\
&=(x+3)(x-3)\purpleC{(x+2)(x-1)}
\end{align}$
